{"cursor":"49477","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n:\"Bahasa Jawi\" redirects here. For the Malay dialect spoken in Pattani,\n:Thailand, see [[Pattani Malay]].\n{{Infobox language |name = Javanese |nativename = (Basa Jawa) |ethnicity =\nJavanese, Osing, Tenggerese |states = Java (Indonesia), Suriname, New Caledonia\n|speakers = 100 million |date = 2011 |ref = Nationalencyklopedin \"VÃ¤rldens\n100 stÃ¶rsta sprÃ¥k 2007\" The World's 100 Largest Languages in 2007\n|familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=SundaâSulawesi |ancestor=Old Javanese\n|script=Javanese alphabet (optional) Pegon alphabet (religious use) Latin\n(general) |iso1=jv|iso2=jav |lc1=jav|ld1=Javanese |lc2=jvn|ld2=Caribbean\nJavanese |lc3=jas|ld3=New Caledonian Javanese |lc4=osi|ld4=Osing\n|lc5=tes|ld5=Tenggerese |lc6=kaw|ld6=Old Javanese |map=Distribution-jv.png\n|mapcaption=Dark green: areas where Javanese is the majority language. Light\ngreen: where it is a minority language. |notice=IPA }}\n\n\n'Javanese' Laurie Bauer, 2007, The Linguistics Studentâs Handbook,\nEdinburgh (Javanese: basa Jawa; ) is the language of the Javanese people\nfrom the central and eastern parts of the island of Java, in Indonesia. There\nare also pockets of Javanese speakers in the northern coast of western Java. It\nis the native language of more than 100,000,000 people (more than 43% of total\npopulation in Indonesia).\n\nJavanese is part of the Austronesian family. Most speakers of Javanese also\nspeak Indonesian for official and commercial purposes, and to communicate with\nnon-Javanese Indonesians.\n\nThere are speakers of Javanese in Malaysia (concentrated in the states of\nSelangor and Johor) and Singapore. Some people of Javanese descent in\nSuriname (the Dutch colony of Suriname until 1975) speak a creole descendant\nof the language.\n","linknr":-1,"url":"Javanese_language","recorded":1372152435,"links":[],"instances":["linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","island","province","dutch_colony","phoneti